# TypeScript Rules

## Core Principles
- Write concise, type-safe TypeScript
- Never use `any` - use `unknown` or proper types
- Use `const` by default, `let` only when needed
- Use functional patterns; avoid classes
- Follow existing patterns in the codebase

## Naming Conventions
- **Files**: `kebab-case.tsx` / `kebab-case.ts`
- **Components**: `PascalCase`
- **Functions/Variables**: `camelCase`
- **Types/Interfaces**: `PascalCase`
- **Schemas**: `[domain]-schemas.ts`

## Variable Naming
- Use descriptive names with auxiliary verbs
- Examples: `isLoading`, `hasError`, `canSubmit`, `shouldRender`

## Code Style
- Use early returns; avoid nested conditionals
- Keep functions short and focused
- Follow Single Responsibility Principle
- Handle errors gracefully with try/catch
- Use implicit type inference when possible
- Use union types of string literals over enums

## Error Handling
```typescript
// tRPC procedures
if (!item) {
  throw new TRPCError({
    code: "NOT_FOUND",
    message: "Item not found",
  });
}

// Client-side
try {
  await mutation.mutateAsync(data);
  toast.success("Saved successfully");
} catch (error) {
  logger.error({ error }, "Operation failed");
  toast.error("Something went wrong");
}
```
